tenaciousD data analysis

Ross Cunning

April 17, 2016

Load libraries and prepare data for analysis

The “setup.R” script loads required libraries and imports data. Total S/H ratios and proportion clade D are calculated for each sample, and corals are categorized as C-dominated or D-dominated based on their dominant symbiont at time zero. Relative changes in Fv/Fm are calculated for each sample. After sourcing this script, the data are ready to be analyzed.

Analyze Fv/Fm data

We utilize generalized additive mixed models (GAMMs) to model relative Fv/Fm values as a smooth function of time, with dominant symbiont clade as a fixed effect and mother colony and core as random effects. We fit separate models for the cooling treatment and the heating treatment. After fitting the models, we simulate from the posterior distribution of the parameters of the fitted models to generate confidence intervals on fitted values. To test whether Fv/Fm differs between C-dominated and D-dominated corals, we generate a confidence interval on the difference between these groups from the simulated values, and test whether it includes zero.

Cooling treatment

# Fit GAMM for cooling treatment
gm.cool <- gamm(rfvfm ~ dom + s(time, by=dom, k=4), random=list(mother=~1, sample=~1), 
                data=subset(data, ramp=="cool"), na.action=na.omit)
summary(gm.cool$gam)
## 
## Family: gaussian 
## Link function: identity 
## 
## Formula:
## rfvfm ~ dom + s(time, by = dom, k = 4)
## 
## Parametric coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  0.74502    0.01146  65.000   <2e-16 ***
## domD        -0.02226    0.01313  -1.695   0.0908 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Approximate significance of smooth terms:
##                edf Ref.df      F p-value    
## s(time):domC 2.919  2.919  393.6  <2e-16 ***
## s(time):domD 2.966  2.966 1127.9  <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## R-sq.(adj) =  0.895   
##   Scale est. = 0.0038023  n = 420
# Get fitted values
pdat.cool <- expand.grid(time=seq(0,63,1), ramp=factor("cool"), dom=factor(c("C", "D")))
gm.cool.pred <- data.frame(cbind(pdat.cool, fit=predict(gm.cool$gam, pdat.cool)))
# Simulate from multivariate normal distribution of fitted model
set.seed(789)
Rbeta <- mvrnorm(n = 1000, coef(gm.cool$gam), vcov(gm.cool$gam))
Xp <- predict(gm.cool$gam, newdata = pdat.cool, type = "lpmatrix")
sim <- Xp %*% t(Rbeta)
# Extract 95% confidence intervals from simulation
gm.cool.pred$lci <- apply(sim, 1, quantile, 0.025)
gm.cool.pred$uci <- apply(sim, 1, quantile, 0.975)

Plot raw data with fitted model

Here, Fv/Fm data (mean ± s.d.) are plotted for clade C- and D-dominated corals, along with the fitted values from the GAMM and 95% confidence intervals.

Test if Fv/Fm is the same in C- and D-dominated corals at each sampling date

# Calculate 95% confidence interval on difference between C and D corals at each sampling dates from simulation
sim1 <- cbind(pdat.cool, sim)
sim1 <- sim1[sim1$time %in% c(0,7,14,21,28,35,42,49,56,63), ]
sim1split <- split(sim1, f=sim1$time, drop=T)
CDdiff.95CI <- lapply(sim1split, function(x) quantile(apply(x[,4:ncol(x)], 2, diff), c(0.025, 0.975)))
# Test if 95% CI on difference between C and D corals contains zero
cool.test0 <- lapply(CDdiff.95CI, FUN=function(x) (x[1] < 0 & 0 < x[2])[[1]])
t(matrix(cool.test0, dimnames=list(day=names(cool.test0), Ho="C-dom = D-dom")))
##                day
## Ho              0    7    14   21    28    35    42    49   56   63  
##   C-dom = D-dom TRUE TRUE TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE TRUE TRUE TRUE

Relative Fv/Fm is significantly higher (p < 0.05) in C-dominated corals than D-dominated corals at day 21, 28, 35, and 42.

Test if Fv/Fm is the same in C- and D-dominated corals at each sampling date

sim1 <- cbind(pdat.heat, sim)

Analyze symbiont abundance (S/H ratios)

Symbiont abundance is analyzed for each treatment using a linear mixed model with log-transformed total symbiont to host cell ratio (S/H ratio) as the response variable, with a fixed effect of time and dominant symbiont clade, and random effects of mother colony and core. After fitting the model, Dunnett’s tests are performed within each group of corals to determine if the total S/H ratio is different from time zero.

Cooling treatment

# Fit linear mixed model
coolSHmod <- lmerTest::lmer(log10(tot.SH) ~ timef * dom + (1|mother/sample), data=subset(data, ramp=="cool"), na.action=na.omit)
summary(coolSHmod)

Analyze dynamics of dominant and non-dominant symbionts together

The previous analysis was on the total symbiont to host cell ratio, but did not distinguish between clade C and D symbionts. Clade D symbionts are present at lower levels in clade C-dominated corals, and vice versa. Here, we analyze the dynamics of both clades simultaneously within C- and D-dominated corals using a linear mixed model approach.

Cooling treatment

# Rearrange data in order to use clade identity as fixed effect in linear model
df <- data[!is.na(data$tot.SH), ]
df2 <- melt(df, id.vars=c(1:6,9:13), value.name="SH")
colnames(df2)[colnames(df2)=="variable"] <- "clade"
# Fit linear mixed model for cooling treatment
coolmod <- lmerTest::lmer(log10(SH) ~ timef * dom * clade + (timef+dom+clade|mother/sample), 
                          data=subset(df2, ramp=="cool"))
print(summary(coolmod), correlation=FALSE)
